The diseases of globalization
Globalization is being subjected to a severe test unlike ever before.
Everywhere its tensions are brewing.
The majority of sub-Saharan Africa, South America, the Middle East and Central Asia are stagnating or struggling with economic decline.
North America, Western Europe and Japan are mired in slow growth and risk a new recession.
The war now threatens Iraq.
For supporters of open markets and free trade, this situation poses major challenges.
Why is globalization so threatened?
Why do its benefits apparently seem concentrated in a few places?
Can a more balanced globalization be implemented?
There is no simple answer to these questions.
Open markets are necessary for economic growth, but they are barely sufficient.
Certain regions of the world have reaped great benefits from globalization, notably East Asia and China in recent years.
Certain regions, however, have reaped meager benefits, particularly Sub-Saharan Africa.
The American government claims that poor countries are responsible for the majority of the problems in which they are struggling.
The slow growth of Africa, say American leaders, is caused by the ineptitude of the African government.
However, life is more complicated than the Bush administration believes.
Consider the best-governed countries in Africa: Ghana, Tanzania, Malawi, The Gambia.
Each of them has experienced declining living standards over the past two decades while many Asian countries that ranked among the lowest in international comparisons of each country's governance (Pakistan, Bangladesh, Myanmar and Sri Lanka) have experienced better economic growth.
It is true that economic performance is determined not only by governance standards, but also by geopolitics, geography and economic structure.
The countries with large populations and therefore large internal markets tend to grow more rapidly than countries with small populations.
(As with all economic trends of this kind, there are counterexamples).
Coastal countries tend to be more successful than landlocked countries.
Countries with high levels of malaria tend to experience slower growth than countries with lower levels of malaria.
Developing countries that border rich markets, such as Mexico, tend to be more successful than countries that are far from major markets.
These differences are of great importance.
If wealthy countries pay little attention to these structural problems, the gaps between the winners and the losers will continue to widen.
If wealthy countries shift the responsibility onto the unfortunate countries by claiming that they are somehow culturally or politically unfit to benefit from globalization, we will not only create deeper pockets of poverty but also intensify the unrest.
This, in turn, will lead to increased levels of violence, hostile reactions, and terrorism.
It is therefore time to move towards a more serious approach to globalization than what is offered by wealthy countries, and particularly the United States.
This approach must begin with the most urgent task, namely meeting the fundamental needs of the world's poorest peoples.
In some cases, their suffering can be alleviated primarily through better governance within their own countries.
But in others, an honest look at the collected evidence will reveal that the main causes of poverty concern diseases, climatic instability, poor soils, market distances, etc.
An honest assessment would further indicate that the poorest countries are unable to raise sufficient funds to solve such problems on their own.
Instead of seeing rich countries give more lessons on the poor governance of poor countries, real solutions require that rich countries provide sufficient financial assistance to overcome the most entrenched barriers.
A case will illustrate this situation in a striking manner.
Disease control requires a health system capable of providing life-saving medicines and basic preventive services such as mosquito nets to fight malaria and vitamins to combat nutritional deficiencies.
This system costs at least about $40 per person per year.
This amount is just a grain of sand for rich countries that systematically spend more than $2,000 per person per year on health, but it exceeds the means of poor countries like Malawi, which have annual incomes of $200 per person.
A functioning health system would cost more than the entire income of its government!
Even though Malawi is well governed, its population will die in large numbers from diseases until it receives adequate assistance.
The success of globalization requires that we think more like doctors and less like preachers.
Instead of scolding the poor for their "sins," we must offer careful diagnoses, as any good doctor would, for each country and region, in order to understand the fundamental factors that delay their economic growth and development.
In some regions like the Andes and Central Asia, the problem mainly comes from geographical isolation.
There, the task is to build roads, air links, and Internet connectivity in order to help these remote regions create productive links with the world.
Rich countries must contribute to funding these projects.
In Sub-Saharan Africa, the main challenges concern disease control, soil fertility, and the development of educational opportunities.
Once again, greater foreign assistance is required.
In other regions, the main problems concern lack of water, discrimination against women or other groups, or a variety of specific issues.
It is now time to take the inherent complexities of globalization seriously.
The ideology of a single size fits all of the Washington consensus is outdated.
On the eve of the war, it is urgent to tackle the difficult task of ensuring that everyone benefits from globalization.
We can achieve this if we remove the ideological blinkers from the wealthy and if we mobilize a partnership between the rich and the poor.
Our common future depends on it.
